NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"> <BR>
Forts&auml;ttning
<H2><CENTER>EU och STIL</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>information om STIL:s<BR>
projekt f&ouml;r HELIOS samarbete</CENTER>
</H3>
<HR>Bilaga 2<BR>
<BR>
<P><CENTER>HELIOS National Information Day in Sweden<BR>
</CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>The HELIOS II Programme - <BR>
a key factor for an active European social policy</CENTER>
</H2>
<P><CENTER><BR>
<BR>
Speech by Mr. Bernhard Wehrens, European Commission <BR>
Head of Division &quot;Integration of disabled people&quot;<BR>
Stockholm, October 30, 1995</CENTER>
<P><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+3">L</FONT>adies and gentlemen,<BR>
<BR>
it is a pleasure for me to represent the European Commission at this 
national
information day. And I would like to thank the Department of Disabled and

Elderly Persons of the Swedish Ministry of health and Social Affairs for
organizing this meeting. I am sure that it will foster the fruitful 
cooperation
that has characterized the relations between Sweden and the EU 
institutions
right from the beginning - since the membership negotiations.<BR>
<BR>
Swedish disability policy is characterized by continued reform work for
disabled people, by individualized measures for disabled people, and by
an extremely active Disability movement. Its central philosophy is that
all human beings have the same value and equal rights. I am convinced, 
that
this will give increased impetus to measures for disabled people 
throughout
all the Member states of the Union - and also to the European Union 
policies
themselves.<BR>
<BR>
My colleague, Philippe Lamoral, Director of the HELlOS Team of Experts,
will be describing what the programme involves and how it works later on.

I would like to map out the general context of European social policy in
which HELIOS II is situated. The future of that policy, and in particular

the issue of a coherent European policy of integration across the board,
is increasingly at the forefront of debate.<BR>
<BR>
Ladies and gentlemen, about 10% of European Union citizens have a severe
disability - and that figure is set to rise. This is due to a large 
extent
to the growing number of victims of road accidents, the trend towards 
childbirth
late in life, and revolutionary advances in medicine and technology, also

the abuse of medicines.<BR>
<BR>
Over the last 10 years - roughly the period covered by the Decade of 
Disabled
Persons declared by the United Nations in 1983 - awareness of the 
interests
of disabled people has grown steadily at EU level, both in theory and in
practice.<BR>
<BR>
With functional rehabilitation, a multidisciplinary approach has 
developed
in which all concerned are involved as equal partners. Technical aids and

new technologies are having a vast impact on virtually every aspect of 
disabled
people lives: from education and training to professional life and 
recreation.
In the field of employment, there are moves to promote integration on the

open labour market. Local and national government increasingly recognize
the need to adapt public buildings and private housing, make public 
transport
user-friendly and improve access to social and cultural activities.<BR>
<BR>
At last, conventional solutions to the everyday problems of disabled 
people
are being revised. The prevailing trend both in the EU institutions and
in the Member States - all with their own national traditions and 
cultures
- is ever further away from segregational support structures, and towards

the integration and full participation of disabled people in the economic

and social life of the community.<BR>
<BR>
One cause of this development is the shift in the disability debate from
the concept of charity to one of civil rights.<BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, we also live in a time of economic recession, which could
jeopardise many of the achievements of recent years if we do not remain
vigilant.<BR>
<BR>
The urgent problem of unemployment, budgetary constraints in the field of

education and training, and above all the difficult position of our 
social
security Systems contribute to a situation in which disabled EU citizens
find themselves at risk of social exclusion - an issue at the heart of 
European
action on social policy.<BR>
<BR>
Equally disturbing is the shift in public opinion brought about by the 
current
economic and financial difficulties. Present conditions are a breeding 
ground
for prejudice and discrimination. As a Belgian psychologist aptly 
remarked
recently, &quot;an unemployed person is not the same as a pensioner: an
unemployed person is a worker without a job, and that is humiliating. 
Increased
support for parties with xenophobic tendencies in some areas is primarily

due to the fact that racism, elevated to the status of ideology, is a way

of projecting that personal sense of humiliation onto others, namely 
aliens''.<BR>
<BR>
Against this background, ladies and gentlemen, there is also a need for
the concept of integration for disabled people to be promoted at local 
level.<BR>
<BR>
Against this background, many disabled people and disability 
organisations
are calling for anti-discrimination legislation on the model of the 1990
Americans with Disabilities Act in the United States.<BR>
<BR>
And it is against this background too that HELlOS should be seen - 
HELlOS,
whose name states its agenda: Handicapped People in the European Union 
Living
Independently in an Open Society.<BR>
<BR>
The HELlOS programme is based on the principle that disabled people are
full citizens, with the same rights and duties as any other citizen. They

are members of what is termed &quot;mainstream&quot; society, and it is
up to that society to ensure their full participation. We cannot go on 
establishing
separate schools, employment structures and accommodation. Instead we 
must
support access to mainstream schooling, encourage employment on the open
labour market, build adapted housing, provide accessible public 
transport,
raise public awareness of the concerns and interests of disabled people
and - last but not least - involve disabled people themselves in the 
development
of measures that concern them. This fundamental principle can be seen at
work in the founding of the European Disability Forum as one of the main
advisory bodies of the HELIOS II programme. But that is not all.<BR>
<BR>
The goal of the HELlOS II programme is integration and equalization of 
opportunities
for the Union's roughly 37 million disabled citizens. The focus is on 
promoting
exchange and information Europe-wide in every area of relevance for 
disabled
people. With the participation of national governments and the relevant
authorities, NGOs, the two sides of industry, specialists, carers, and -
most importantly of all - disabled people themselves and their 
representatives.<BR>
<BR>
The principle on which this cooperation is based is as simple as it is 
effective:
crossborder dialogue and comparison, and thereby the transfer of know-how

and good practice. There are promising developments and innovative 
practices
to be seen in every EU Member State, which are well worth crossing the 
border
for. That is why we place such emphasis on international comparison. We
rely on our partners in each Member State to give colleagues in other 
countries
an opportunity to learn from their experience - and to feed what they 
themselves
learn from European cooperation back into the right channels in their own

countries. This crossfertilisation is the cornerstone of the programme,
underpinned by multidisciplinary transnational partnerships and practical

cooperation at grassroots level.<BR>
<BR>
The HELlOS programme operates on five fronts, which my colleague, 
Philippe
Lamoral, will present in greater detail later. They are:
<DL>
  <DD>exchange and information activities,
  <DD>cooperation with disability organisations,
  <DD>public information and awareness-raising,
  <DD>information on technical aids (the HANDYNET system),
  <DD>working groups on employment, education, sport, tourism and 
transport.
</DL>
<BR>
Particular emphasis is placed on the development of multiplier effects 
with
other Community programmes and initiatives of interest to disabled 
people.
This includes the TIDE initiative on new technologies for disabled and 
elderly
people, the new education programmes SOCRATES, LEONARDO and Youth for 
Europe
III, and the Employment-HORIZON initiative, whose activities include 
promoting
vocational training and economic integration for disabled people.<BR>
<BR>
The organisation and content of the HELlOS programme's activities will be

described in detail later. What I would like to discuss here is the 
principle
of subsidiarity enshrined in the Maastricht treaty, as it affects 
European
social policy.<BR>
<BR>
In practical terms, subsidiarity means as much unity as possible with as
much decentralisation as is necessary. In the context of European 
disability
policy, the HELIOS programme is judged by the European Parliament to be
a exemplary model of the subsidiarity principle at work. The 
participating
projects in the exchange and information activities are designated by the

Member States. The precise form of activities is determined by the 
partners
within the framework of priority themes laid down for the duration of 
HELIOS
II.<BR>
<BR>
All activities conducted under HELlOS II are submitted to the programme's

advisory bodies for an opinion. These bodies are:
<UL>
  <LI>the Advisory Committee, composed of two government representatives
from each of the Member States;
  <LI>the European Disability Forum, comprising representatives of 12 
NGOs,
15 national disability councils or representative national NGOs and the
two sides of industry;
  <LI>the Liaison Group, a forum for constructive debate between 
government
representatives and NGOs.
</UL>
Also in recognition of the subsidiarity principle, the focus is not on 
binding
legislative provisions. Instead the programme's aim is to develop Guides
of good practice in five distinct fields: functional rehabilitation, 
integration
in the field of education, economic integration (that is preparation for
employment and employment), and social integration and independent 
living.
Following an open invitation to tender, an independent body-Edinburgh's
Telford College - was commissioned to draft these guides. They will be 
produced
on the basis of information gathered from the various strands of activity

of the HELIOS II programme. Philippe Lamoral will give you further 
details
in this respect.<BR>
<BR>
In other words, decisions relating to disabled Union citizens are not 
arbitrary
edicts from Brussels. The primary architect of European social 
legislation
is always the individual Member State - with the participation of 
disabled
people and their representatives.<BR>
<BR>
However, we can develop an awareness of common goals. Many problems can
no longer be solved unilaterally at national level but call for concerted

action by all the European partners.<BR>
<BR>
In this sense, the HELIOS II programme can be said to be a rallying point

for the combined forces of all the Member States. This is a formidable 
basis
on which to develop a general European framework for provisions in the 
individual
States. And it is at national level that the Guides of good practice due
to be produced by the end of the programme in 1996 will, while not 
legally
binding, fuel political debate and - hopefully - prompt fresh legislative

action.<BR>
<BR>
Ladies and gentlemen, a glance back over the last 20 years of European 
action
to assist disabled people reveals that it is largely in the last decade
that the prospect of a concerted strategy has emerged. Organisations of
and for disabled people have acquired a voice at all levels of political
activity. There is growing recognition that measures for disabled people
should not be limited to the European Commission's activities in the 
social
field. Broader-based Community programmes and initiatives are 
increasingly
drawing on the potential of disabled people.<BR>
<BR>
This trend towards &quot;mainstreaming&quot; is one we must maintain for
the future.<BR>
<BR>
The 1987 Single European Act solidly underpinned the principle of 
economic
and social solidarity in providing for structures for social dialogue 
between
employers and trade unions.<BR>
<BR>
With the ratification of Maastricht in late 1994, the agreement on social

policy contained in the treaty came into force, with its objectives of 
&quot;the
promotion of employment, improved living and working conditions, proper
social protection, dialogue between the social partners, the development
of human resources with a view to lasting high employment and the 
combatting
of exclusion.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Just recently we saw the first practical expression of that 
commitment.<BR>
<BR>
In April, the Commission submitted its Medium Term Social Action 
Programme
for the next three years - 1995 to 1997 - to the Council, the European 
Parliament,
the Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions. The
programme is the third and final stage in a consultation process which 
began
in 1993 with the publication of the Green Paper on the future of European

social policy and continued in 1994 with the White Paper on European 
Social
Policy.<BR>
<BR>
The White Paper set out a framework for the development of European 
social
policy. It was based on the principle that Europe needs a 
forward-looking,
innovative social policy if it is to meet the economic and social 
challenges
ahead.<BR>
<BR>
The social action programme is the direct result of a broad process of 
consultation
at all levels on the strategies set out in the White Paper. Five themes
are of particular importance.<BR>
<BR>
Firstly, the process of European integration should, in accordance with
the subsidiarity principle, safeguard the diversity of national cultures
and practices. The aim of the Union is to achieve not complete uniformity

in the social field, but policy convergence.<BR>
<BR>
Second, continuing economic integration in the EU and the completion of
the single market must work in favour and not to the detriment of Union
citizens. Social policy is one of the principal instruments for achieving

this.<BR>
<BR>
Third, job creation remains top priority. A vigorous followup to the 
White
Paper &quot;Growth, Competitiveness, Employment&quot; and the conclusions

of the European Council meeting in Essen is therefore called for.<BR>
<BR>
Fourth, a new balance needs to be struck between the economic and social
dimensions. They should be seen as mutually complementary, rather than 
competing,
objectives.<BR>
<BR>
And fifth, Community action in the social field cannot be confined to the

world of work. Complementary economic and social policy measures are 
needed,
offering Union citizens &quot;opportunities for all&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
The catalogue of measures proposed in the social action programme cover
such areas as the priority issue of jobs, education and training, equal
opportunities for men and women, social protection, public health and 
more
effective application of existing European law. A number of proposals 
relate
directly or indirectly to the concerns of disabled people in the Europe
of the future. We have drawn up a corresponding programme of work in 
eight
key areas.<BR>
<BR>
Firstly, the social action programme states that the Commission intends
to focus on the issue of the employment of disabled people - particularly

in relation to new technologies and communications systems - in the 
follow-up
to the conclusions of the European Council meeting in Essen. Furthermore,

Union-wide discussions are planned as part of the social dialogue over 
the
course of 1996 on promoting good practice among employers, with the 
involvement
of the trade unions. We intend to draw up a strategic document in 
collaboration
with other Commission departments, national governments, NGOs and the two

sides of industry, which should lead on to a European initiative in 1997.

Central to this, we feel, must be participation by disabled people in 
&quot;mainstream&quot;
European Union programmes - a need highlighted in the White Paper on 
European
Social Policy.<BR>
<BR>
Second, over the course of this year the Commission is to draft a code of

good practice on the employment of disabled people at the Commission 
itself
and in other European institutions.<BR>
<BR>
Third, the Commission will issue a communication before the end of 1995
on the measures needed to eliminate the discriminatory barriers still 
faced
by disabled people in Europe.<BR>
<BR>
Fourth, in the interests of greater freedom of movement, the Commission
will be presenting a recommendation before the end of the year on the 
mutual
recognition of parking permits for disabled people.<BR>
<BR>
Fifth, the Commission will be stepping up pressure for the adoption of 
the
proposal for a directive on minimum requirements to improve the mobility
and the safe transport to work of workers with reduced mobility, 
submitted
in 1991 .<BR>
<BR>
Sixth, the Commission intends to issue a recommendation in 1996 on the 
practical
application within the EU of the Standard Rules on the Equalisation of 
Opportunities
for Persons with Disabilities adopted by the UN General Assembly in 1993.

This is in line with the White Paper's proposal that the principle of 
equal
opportunities should be enshrined in all EU measures and an 
&quot;appropriate
instrument endorsing the UN standard rules&quot; prepared.<BR>
<BR>
A seventh key aspect of the social action programme is the planned 
Commission
proposal for a decision establishing a disability forum with a broader 
remit.
The new forum would advise on disability issues in all fields of 
Community
policy and activity.<BR>
<BR>
The eighth and final key point set out in the social action programme is
the possible measures to continue European action in this field after the

HELlOS II programme reaches its term at the end of 1996. While awaiting
the interim evaluation of the programme by an independent body due to be
completed this year, the Commission has recently started wide-ranging 
consultations
in preparation for a proposal for a Council decision on the establishment

of a fourth Community action programme to assist disabled people, to be
adopted before the end of 1996.<BR>
<BR>
I cannot comment on the content of the new programme, as preparatory work

has only just begun. But what is in no doubt is the Commission's wish to
continue building upon cooperation - with NGOs and information exchange
through crossborder partnerships at local level. Both factors are crucial

for the implementation of two key features of the social action 
programme:
the recommendation on the practical implementation of the 1993 UN 
Standard
Rules on the Equalisation of Opportunities for Persons with Disabilities
and the communication on eliminating discrimination. We are firmly 
convinced
that those responsible for developing and implementing measures in these
areas should look to the experience of the Member States and the positive

practices perhaps already in use there. The Guides of good practice will
be equally useful in this respect.<BR>
<BR>
Ladies and gentlemen, one of the European Commission's aims in putting 
forward
the social action programme is to place greater emphasis on the social 
dimension
of Europe in the negotiations surrounding the intergovernmental 
conference
on the Maastricht reform.<BR>
<BR>
A key point will be the proposal set out in the White Paper for the 
inclusion
of a specific reference to combatting discrimination on various grounds
- disability included - at the forthcoming review of the Treaty on 
European
Union. The Commission will also be doing all it can to ensure that 
principle
is put into effect.<BR>
<BR>
The past few years have been a time of restructuring in European social
policy, which provides a practical framework for achieving equality for
disabled people in society. This process takes on a new dimension with 
the
enlargement of the Union to three new Member States and the forthcoming
cooperation - under the HELlOS II programm - with Iceland, Liechtenstein
and Norway and central and eastern European countries<BR>
<BR>
The changes are not confined to Europe alone: the whole world order is 
shifting.
That is why it is so very important for the European Union, with its 
partners,
to choose the right path forward - for Europe an its disabled citizens.
<P><CENTER><HR><FONT SIZE="-1">[ <A 
