NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"> <BR>
Forts&auml;ttning
<H2><CENTER>EU och STIL</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>information om STIL:s<BR>
projekt f&ouml;r HELIOS samarbete</CENTER>
</H3>
<HR>Bilaga 3<BR>
<H2>HEART</H2>
<BR>
Improving service delivery systems for assistive technology - a European
strategy<BR>
<BR>
The HEART (Horizontal European Activities in Rehabilitation Technology)
project is a joint effort among 16 European countries to study the 
rehabilitation
technology market and service delivery systems for the disabled and 
elderly,
emphasizing the consumer/user's point of view.<BR>
<BR>
HEART is funded by TIDE (Technology for the Integration of the Disabled
and Elderly). The TIDE programme is a Community initiative to develop new

technological tools and applications for people with disabilities and 
elderly
people, to enable them to live independently and participate fully in the

social and economic activities of the community.<BR>
<BR>
The HEART study focused on six areas in assistive technology, with each
area pursued by a line: 
<DL>
  <DD>Line A: Testing and Standardization 
  <DD>Line B: Industrial Coherence 
  <DD>Line C: Service Delivery 
  <DD>Line D: Legal and Economic Factors 
  <DD>Line E: Training of Professionals 
  <DD>Line F: Emerging Areas of Technology Research and Development 
</DL>
Our aim in Line C was to propose improvements in the service delivery of
assistive technology in Europe. This can be achieved in two ways: through

stimulation of an international assistive technology market and through
an ongoing improvement of quality of the services. The first task of Line

C was to describe service delivery in the 16 countries. These 
descriptions
are collected in the book &quot;European Service Delivery Systems in 
Rehabilitation
Technology.&quot; In this book we describe the structure of each system
against the background of each country's political and social policy. The

process itself was described in terms of seven steps. We then examined 
the
descriptions on the basis of six quality criteria in an effort to find 
good
examples of service delivery. These results were presented and discussed
at an international workshop in Belluno, Italy.<BR>
<BR>
Professional cooperation on this study was among three institutions: the
Institute for Rehabilitation Research (IRV) in the Netherlands, The 
Swedish
Handicap Institute in Sweden, and Fondazione Pro Juventute Don C. Gnocchi

(SIVA) in Italy. Representatives from 13 other national centres also 
contributed
to the study, as well as experts from user organizations.<BR>
<BR>
In spreading the results of this study we hope to improve communication
between countries about service delivery and start a discussion about how

to improve service delivery systems.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
A FEW DEFINITIONS<BR>
<BR>
Service delivery: The structures and processes by which a person with a
disability or impairment can receive assistive technology and related 
services
such as information and training.<BR>
<BR>
Assistive technology: Any product, instrument, equipment or technical 
system
used by a disabled person, especially produced or generally available, 
preventing,
compensating, relieving or neutralizing the impairment, disability or 
handicap.
This is the definition used by the ISO 9999 Classification of Technical
Aids for Disabled Persons. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
WHY CARE ABOUT SERVICE DELIVERY?<BR>
<BR>
The need for assistive technology in Europe is expected to increase 
rapidly
in the coming years. At the same time, the swift pace of technological 
improvement
will offer both challenges and opportunities to users and to those who 
provide
such technology.<BR>
<BR>
But while demands are increasing, budgets are shrinking. In many European

countries, public spending is being cut. This is deeply felt in the 
health
care and social service sectors. To meet the challenge of maintaining --
and, more importantly, improving -- service delivery in this climate, the

efficiency and effectiveness must be improved.<BR>
<BR>
A European Strategy<BR>
<BR>
A major goal of the European Commission is to stimulate communication and

understanding between countries, and to share ideas, experiences, and 
knowledge
in such a way that all countries can benefit.<BR>
<BR>
The need for greater exchange across borders is particularly relevant in
the field of assistive technology. The situation today is very complex:
countries have very diverse systems and even within each country, the 
system
is often complex and difficult to understand and describe.<BR>
<BR>
However, we believe that disabled and elderly people every where in 
Europe
can benefit from a greater exchange of information across borders. We 
believe
that expansion of the assistive technology market on a European level 
will
stimulate those in the market to improve quality, to reduce prices and to

involve users-consumers in the process.<BR>
<BR>
To facilitate communication in the field of assistive technology, it's 
useful
to have a common terminology. To that end, we have developed the seven 
steps
which can be used to describe the service delivery process in any 
country.<BR>
<BR>
We believe that to improve efficiency and effectiveness, while at the 
same
time increasing the transparency of service delivery systems, a quality
development process guided by internationally accepted criteria has the
best chance of success.<BR>
<BR>
With that in mind, we developed the six quality criteria outlined here.
We encourage every country to use these criteria when evaluating and 
improving
their systems. Those involved in service delivery should also study 
different
European countries to see what guidance and examples of excellence they
offer.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
WHERE WE BEGAN<BR>
<BR>
Accessibility<BR>
<BR>
Service delivery systems for assistive technology are not isolated. They
are an integral part of other systems, such as rehabilitation, 
habilitation,
medical and social services.<BR>
<BR>
Therefore, assistive technology is just one way to compensate for or 
minimize
the functional limitations of people with disabilities. Other 
possibilities
include medical treatment, therapy or training, counseling and personal
assistance. Service delivery needs to be seen in the complete context, 
and
an appropriate mix of measures needs to be tailored to each person with
disabilities.<BR>
<BR>
We have defined six criteria for good service delivery systems: 
<DL>
  <DD>Accessibility 
  <DD>Competence 
  <DD>Coordination 
  <DD>Efficiency 
  <DD>Flexibility 
  <DD>User influence 
</DL>
These criteria are closely related to each other and can sometimes 
conflict
with each other.<BR>
<BR>
The best service delivery system in the world is of little use if it's 
not
accessible to those who need it. Consequently, we studied this criterion
from the users' perspective.<BR>
<BR>
Accessibility means that people know where to go for help, that the 
system
is easy to understand and that ample information about it is 
available.<BR>
<BR>
Accessibility is based on the needs of the individual. It also means that

the system has a broad scope. No one should be excluded because of age,
type or cause of disability, where they live or ability to pay.<BR>
<BR>
Competence<BR>
<BR>
The competence of the people working in a service delivery system 
determines
how good it is. Competence means that personnel have the knowledge, 
skills
and experience necessary to provide proper service to the users of the 
system,
people with disabilities.<BR>
<BR>
Professionals in service delivery come from very diverse fields: 
medicine,
psychology, rehabilitation, engineering and social work. Educational and
training levels are often very varied. Indications of the competence of
the professionals in the system, include not only the educational level
of the professionals, but also the possibilities for further education,
access to information, what opportunities there are to learn from user 
feedback
and the level of decision making power professionals have in the service
delivery process.<BR>
<BR>
Coordination<BR>
<BR>
As in all systems, the parts of the whole must be well )coordinated in 
order
to provide good service. Coordination can be viewed on three levels: 
<DL>
  <DD>Between the individual and all steps in the delivery process 
  <DD>Between the professionals working with service delivery 
  <DD>Between the service delivery system and other sectors of society 
</DL>
Efficiency<BR>
<BR>
Because demand for assistive technology is increasing, is vital that 
service
delivery is as efficient as possible.<BR>
<BR>
Efficiency means the capacity to find the best solutions for the greatest

number of people, using available resources at the lowest cost, in the 
shortest
possible time.<BR>
<BR>
Flexibility<BR>
<BR>
Systems must respond to change and allow for individual differences, 
which
means they need to be flexible. Flexibility is vital for assistive 
technology
because of the diverse nature of disabilities and constant technological
advances.<BR>
<BR>
A service delivery system is flexible when: 
<UL>
  <LI>potential users can get devices that meet their needs whether or 
not
those devices are on an approved list or are marketed in the countries 
where
users live, 
  <LI>producer-importers can get a device tested at a reasonable cost, 
within
a reasonable time, 
  <LI>researchers and developers can get financial support for their 
work,
cooperate and communicate with users, designers and producers, and 
utilize
new technology to meet needs 
</UL>
<BR>
User influence<BR>
<BR>
Users are the final judges of quality in service delivery. User 
empowerment
in a service delivery system is strongly dependent on the information 
available
and on their legal rights in general.<BR>
<BR>
Indicators of user influence include: 
<DL>
  <DD>the presence and strength of user organizations 
  <DD>legal rights and their enforcement 
  <DD>user involvement on the policy-making level 
  <DD>frequent user consultation during the process 
  <DD>user influence in the decision making process 
</DL>
<BR>
SEVEN ESSENTIAL STEPS<BR>
<BR>
Service delivery of assistive technology should be an integrated part of
rehabilitation or habilitation. However, for the sake of discussion, the
process can be described in seven essential steps: 
<UL>
  <LI>Initiative The first contact 
  <LI>Assessment Evaluation of needs 
  <LI>Typology Choosing the appropriate kind of assistive technology 
  <LI>Selection Selecting the specific device 
  <LI>Authorization Obtaining funding 
  <LI>Delivery Getting the device to the user 
  <LI>Management and follow-up Continued help for the user 
</UL>
Regardless of the country, the process can usually be described in these
seven steps. However, there may also be differences within countries 
depending
on the type of disability, the type of assistive technology and age of 
the
users.<BR>
<BR>
The case of Robert<BR>
<BR>
Although procedures for service delivery differ in each of the 16 
countries
surveyed, the criteria for a good system and the seven steps of the 
process
can be described in a similar manner. With that in mind, let's look at 
the
following example, which illustrates the process.<BR>
<BR>
Robert has a low spinal cord injury from an auto accident. He has been in

the hospital, but will soon be able to leave.<BR>
<BR>
In this instance, a professional would take the initiative. Robert would
come into close contact with occupational therapists or physical 
therapists
while in the hospital.<BR>
<BR>
The professional will make an assessment of the need for assistive 
technology
and other rehabilitation measures.<BR>
<BR>
Following the assessment, Robert and the hospital professionals will 
discuss
the typology of different solutions and together choose the appropriate
assistive technology, in this case a manual wheelchair.<BR>
<BR>
The next step is selection of the specific wheelchair Robert and the 
therapist
will look at several models and Robert will have the opportunity to test
drive them.<BR>
<BR>
Obtaining funding for a wheelchair differs from country to country. It 
usually
involves authorization of a professional and/or application to an 
insurance
authority.<BR>
<BR>
Delivery is made to the hospital, where Robert receives training in using

the chair.<BR>
<BR>
For management and follow-up wup, Robert may turn to the prescribing 
therapist
or a local district therapist.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
WHERE IS SERVICE DELIVERY GOING?<BR>
<BR>
Demand<BR>
<BR>
As mentioned earlier, the trend is toward increased need for good service

delivery systems, partly because the European population is ageing. Many
users of assistive technology are in this group. In addition, there's a
trend toward emphasizing home care for these people instead of 
institutionalization.
Home care offers new challenges for service delivery systems.<BR>
<BR>
In the coming years, we can also expect more knowledgeable and 
sophisticated
users. Older people today have very different expectations for their 
lives
compared with previous generations. Many will be used to a higher living
standard and they will require -- and be able to use -- high tech 
solutions
to solve the problems tied to everyday activities.<BR>
<BR>
At the same time, the general education level of the population is 
increasing
and many countries are improving the educational opportunities for people

with disabilities.<BR>
<BR>
For all age groups, the potential benefits of assistive technology are 
becoming
better known. As a result, more people are demanding the technology which

can help to improve their quality of life.<BR>
<BR>
Economic trends<BR>
<BR>
Even as demand is increasing, many countries are experiencing economic 
difficulties,
leading to cutbacks in public spending. These are being keenly felt in 
the
health and social service sectors, increasing the need for cost 
effectiveness.<BR>
<BR>
The trend is also toward decentralization of services and more service 
providers.
Decentralized services can lead to closer contact between users and 
providers.
However it can also sharpen the differences in the opportunities to 
obtain
service and in the quality of service provided. This could accentuate 
inequalities
in service delivery systems.<BR>
<BR>
New technology<BR>
<BR>
High technology is increasingly pervading society, and this trend is 
reflected
in service delivery.<BR>
<BR>
The new technology presents both challenges and opportunities. The first
challenge is to utilize technological advances for the benefit of people
with disabilities.<BR>
<BR>
Doing so improves both the assistive devices themselves and the service
delivery process. Information technology, for instance, can improve the
dissemination of information and spread it through several kinds of 
media,
depending on the target audience.<BR>
<BR>
The second challenge is to develop technology in all areas of society so
that it is user friendly from the start. The term &quot;use needs to 
include
disabled and older people. By designing technology for everyone, many 
possibilities
will be opened for these people. This concept is sometimes referred to as

design for all, universal design, or barrier-free design.<BR>
<BR>
At the same time that it is important to utilize and improve new, 
high-tech
devices, it is vital not to neglect traditional, low-tech solutions, 
which
are often essential and inexpensive. For example, a blind person might 
need
both computer peripherals and a white cane.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
WHAT'S NEXT?<BR>
<BR>
Each country in our study has its own service delivery system, developed
according to social, political, economic and cultural traditions.<BR>
<BR>
The HEART consortium cannot prescribe how individual countries should 
organize
their systems. But, as noted earlier, the six quality criteria are 
relevant
to all service delivery systems, regardless of where in the world they 
are.
What we hope to do through this study is to start a discussion both on 
national
and international levels about the quality of service delivery.<BR>
<BR>
In order to improve the quality of service delivery, it is necessary to
develop tools to evaluate systems and to exchange knowledge and 
experiences.
Collection and dissemination of information about service delivery needs
to continue, both domestically and internationally.<BR>
<BR>
Improvement cannot come about overnight. The process must be gradual, 
based
on consensus, and the differences among countries must be respected. We
firmly believe this approach will work, based on our experience in this
study.<BR>
<BR>
Actions by the European Commission can increase awareness of service 
delivery
systems and promote research in the field. As part of this process, we 
think
that all programs supported by the Commission should take into account 
disability
issues.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
MORE SPECIFICALLY<BR>
<BR>
On the basis of this study, we have developed a number of recommendations

which we believe are essential to improve service delivery systems. Some
of these recommendations need to be carried out on a European level. 
Others
are relevant for action on a national or local level.<BR>
<BR>
Networking and Information 
<UL>
  <LI>Create a European coordinating structure for spreading information
and facilitating information exchange. 
  <LI>Make an inventory of existing outstanding centres in Europe with 
specialized
competence in different areas of assistive technology. 
  <LI>Create an international network between centres 
  <LI>Make the Handynet system more available and accessible to the 
public.
Make the system part of a wider strategy for transferring information and

knowledge. 
  <LI>Organize training and courses on an international level, taking 
into
account national, cultural and regional differences. 
  <LI>Develop and validate protocols for the steps in the service 
delivery
process. 
  <LI>Update the descriptions of the service delivery systems in 
&quot;European
Service Delivery Systems in Rehabilitation Technology&quot; in early 1996

  <LI>Organize an international workshop to discuss service delivery in
1996, as a follow-up to the Belluno work-shop. 
</UL>
<BR>
Terminology<BR>
<BR>
* Terminology in the field should be clarified, through a study.<BR>
<BR>
User Influence 
<UL>
  <LI>Initiate studies to develop methods for systematically collecting
user feedback. 
  <LI>Support studies to look at user involvement in all aspects of 
service
delivery 
  <LI>Organize a European pilot project to investigate financial support
to user organizations, in order to increase their influence in service 
delivery.
</UL>
<BR>
Evaluation and Development of Quality Assurance 
<UL>
  <LI>Initiate a study to develop common procedures for evaluating 
service
delivery systems based on the six criteria. 
  <LI>Develop tools, procedures and expertise needed to make service 
delivery
systems self-correcting. 
  <LI>Create measuring tools which look not only at what the system is 
doing
but also why. 
  <LI>Study financial and administrative procedures within service 
delivery
to help eliminate bureaucratic rules, complicated financial requirements
and administrative barriers that can draw out the process unnecessarily
  <LI>Systems should be studied to develop methods for analyzing cost 
efficiency.
</UL>
<BR>
Cross-Border Possibilities<BR>
<BR>
* With the European Union Treaty opening up the chances for movement 
within
Europe, a study should be done to determine how disabled people can 
easily
receive help outside their home countries.<BR>
<BR>
Service, Maintenance and Repair<BR>
<BR>
* Initiate a study to identify and develop good solutions.<BR>
<BR>
Uncommon Disabilities 
<UL>
  <LI>Formulate development plans for small groups of people with 
uncommon
disabilities. 
  <LI>Stimulate and support competence centres, both European and 
regional.
  <LI>Stimulate international agreements concerning the production of 
devices
produced on a small scale. 
</UL>
We hope that this brochure can stimulate discussion leading to 
international
and national actions to develop and improve service delivery of assistive

technology in Europe.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
FOR MORE INFORMATION<BR>
<BR>
Available reports from line C:<BR>
C.5.1 Final report on service delivery, technical report.<BR>
C.5.2 Final report on service delivery, condensed version.<BR>
C.6.1 Recommendations for making improvements in service delivery systems

of assistive technology.<BR>
<BR>
The reports can be ordered from<BR>
The Swedish Handicap Institute,<BR>
P.O. Box 510, S-162 15 Vallingby,<BR>
Sweden.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+3">L</FONT><BR>
